Project: No-show appointments¶

by Nervana Mosaad¶

Why do 30% of patients miss their scheduled appointments?
A person makes a doctor appointment, receives all the instructions and no-show. Who to blame?

Introduction¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row. It provides us information about patient ID, gender, the day patient registered an appointment(Scheduled day), the day when patient has to visit the doctor(Appointment day), age of patient, neighbourhood (where patient will visit doctor), scholarship(indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família., chornic diseases (hipertension, diabetes, handcap, alcoholism).

Here is the variables we will discuss No-show appointments.

You can see original source on Kaggle to know more about the dataset and columns.

It is important to explore what factors to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?¶

Find trends amoung patients who showed their scheduled appointments and how they differed from patients who didn't show up.

Some important questions to be answered:¶

  • What is higher percentage gender, male or female?
  • Is there a relationship between age and having a scholarship?
  • What is relationship between scholarship and gender?
  • What is the ratio of people attending and missing appointment?
  • Does a waiting time interval have any affect on people showing up for appointment?
  • Which age category is more affected by diseases?
  • Is there a relation between sms recieved and missing appointments?
  • Is diabetes more common in male or female?
  • Does sms recieved relate with a specific diesease?
  • Does sms recieved relate with a specific age category?
  • Does no-show count have a correlation with ages?
  • Does no-show count have a correlation with receiving SMS?
  • Does no-show count have a correlation with the living area?
  • What is the ratio between genders, the likelihood of somebody showing up, and the age distribution in the dataset?
  • Checking if there is any relationship between peoples personal ailment and no-shows

Data Cleaning¶

  • Renaming column labels according to PEP 8 – Style Guide for Python Code.

  • PatientId should be intger dtype and 12 14 num.

  • Setting patientid as index.

  • Set gender 'male' instead of M and 'female' instead of F.

  • ScheduledDay should be datetime.

  • AppointmentDay should be datetime.

  • Neighbourhood convert cell to title characters instead of uppercase characters.

  • There is patient whose age equal -1 will be moved to a separate dataframe and also the age of 115 (outlier).

In [54]:
# rename columns 
df.rename(columns={"PatientId":"patient_id","AppointmentID":"appointment_id","ScheduledDay":"scheduled_day"
                   ,"AppointmentDay":"appointment_day","No-show":"no_show"},inplace=True)
df.columns = df.columns.str.lower()

In [12]:
#- set gender male instead of M and female instead of F 

df.gender = df.gender.apply(lambda male : male.replace("M","male"))
df.gender = df.gender.apply(lambda female : female.replace("F","female"))
In [13]:
## split appointment_day to only date  and convert it into to datetime  
df.appointment_day = df.appointment_day.apply(lambda x : x.split('T')[0])
df['appointment_day'] = pd.to_datetime(df['appointment_day'])
In [14]:
# split scheduled_day to day and time :
df.scheduled_day = df.scheduled_day.apply(lambda x : x.split('T')[0])

# convert scheduled_day to datatime
df['scheduled_day'] = pd.to_datetime(df['scheduled_day'])

# day_difference between appointment_day and scheduled_day
# Would be used later to asnwer questions
df['day_difference'] =  df['appointment_day'] - df['scheduled_day'] 
df['day_difference'] = df.day_difference.astype(str).apply(lambda x :x.split(' ')[0]).astype(int)
df.insert(6,"day_difference",df.pop("day_difference"))

def write_text_on_axis(xlabel,ylabel,title): 
    """ this functios is used to take 
     (str)  xlabel  string to write it on x-axis of plot 
     (str)  ylabel  string to write it on y-axis of plot 
     (str)  title   string to make it as title of plot 
    
    """
    plt.xlabel(xlabel) 
    plt.ylabel(ylabel,fontsize=12)
    plt.title(title)

def illnes_and_life_style(illness): 
    
    ''' 
    plots relation of illness and life stage?
    this function  is used for get data of patients  disease to get the percentage  
    of patients with it and patients without it  for each life stage then draw a bar chart for this
    
    
    (str) illness     string of  illness to get the percentage  of patients with it  and patients without it 
    ''' 
    temp = df.copy()                        # get copy of data frame  for not modifing the  orginal data
    temp[f"has {illness}"]=df[illness]!=0   # make a columns to check the patiens have specific disease or not 
    
    # get the precentage of each life stage have specific disease  and precentage of not having 
    illness_num_lifestage=temp.groupby("life_stage")[f"has {illness}"].value_counts(normalize=True).mul(100).unstack() 
    # make a bar chart between lif stage and precentage 
    illness_num_lifestage.plot.bar(edgecolor="black", rot=0, width=.8, stacked=True, figsize=[14,4])
    # to write good strings on axis xlabel andd ylabel and title 
    write_text_on_axis("life stage","percentage",f"Life stages of {illness} patients")

Conclusions¶

  • We analyzed No-show appointments dataset to show what are the reasons that make patients miss their scheduled appointments, and What factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?

  • With the analysis, we come up with some useful information which would help us predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment:

  • There are 79.8% from total number of patients showed up to their appointment, only 20.2% did not show up the appointment.
  • About 75% of patients show up doesn't have illnesses (Hipertension - Alcoholism - Handcap).
  • Patients show up have average age about 38 years.
  • The data is of about 71,839% female patients and 38,687% male.

  • About 7 males and 6 female have all illness (Hipertension - Alcoholism - Handcap - Diabetes).

  • Contrary to expected, the scholarship is completely unrelated to any specific feature of patients. Maybe, it is related with financial status of patient.

  • we suppose that there is a relation between people who no show up to their appointment and waiting time interval, difference between appointment day and sheduled day, but from analysis we found that time interval has affect on showing up to appointment.

  • Age of patients range from 0 and 115 years old with median 37 and average age of 38. We split their ages into groups:
    Infant = 0-1 year
    Toddler = 2-4 yrs
    Child = 5-12 yrs
    Teen = 13-19 yrs
    Adult = 20-39 yrs (27%)
    Middle Age Adult = 40-59 yrs (About 28% of patients)
    Senior Adult = 60+ (19.8%)

(Patients less than 18 years are about 25.1%)

  • We discussed the age categories affected by deseases and it shows that:
  • the Most age group are affected by choric diseases is senior adult and then middle age adult.
  • percentage of diseases in each gender :
  • For Hypertension, about 54.8% from senior adult male and 52.8% from senior adult female.
    It indicate that hypertension more common among males.
  • For Diabetes, 58% from senior adult male and 58.8 from female. There is no significantly difference.
  • For Alcoholism, about 57.8% from middle age adult male drinks alcohol, compared to 54.9% from female.
  • On the other hand, about 31.3% from adult female drinks alcocol against 13.5% from male.
    That indicates adult female are more addictive to alcohol compared to male.

  • Also, we found that SMS recieved by patients is more common among people with Hypertension which may indicate the neighbourhood interest and cares with Hypertension.

  • It's important to discuss the neighbourhood and explore when and where it's more crowded to be solved later:

  • The top ten neighbourhood whose pateints have scholarship are: (in ascending values) [Andorinhas, Santo André, Bonfim, São Benedito, Gurigica, Santa Martha, Caratoíra, Resistência, Tabuazeiro, Ilha Do Príncipe ].

  • About 16% of patient go to hospital more than one the maximum number of times a patient went to hospital is 87 without show up.

  • The day of 2016-06-6 have max number of appointments about 4692 and the neighbourhood have max capacity is Jardim Camburi.

Limitations¶

  • The data was sufficient to prove my findings without wrangling much data.
  • There is patient whose age equal -1, I've moved the whole row to a separate dataframe
  • Ignored the patient of age 115 years old (outlier) within my analysis.
